Abstract = {The effectiveness of long-term retardants used in forest fire fighting
   has been studied at three different scales. In this paper, retardant
   effectiveness experiments conducted since 1965 are examined and
   reviewed. These experiments include studies carried out with analytical
   instrumentation as well as studies involving laboratory and field
   flame-spread tests. Special attention is paid to the work performed with
   diammonium phosphate (DAP) and ammonium sulfate (AS). The experimental
   methodologies and the results obtained are reviewed in detail. A lack of
   effort in the modeling of fire behavior under the effect of these
   products is evidenced and recommendations for further work are made. (C)
   2008 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.},
